; cell-sync-transport.form — a cell learned on one device reaches another, content-addressed.
;
; RUNNABLE HEART: form-stdlib/cell-sync.fk proves the diff/verify/consent LOGIC four-way (cs-missing =
; the want-set · cs-accept-count = re-address verify · cs-shareable = the consent filter; band -> 127).
; The wire FRAMES over a carrier and peer discovery remain BUILDABLE/carrier-work, named below.
;
; THE ASK (the gap shared-sensing.form names, step 3 of its path):
;   "We share Form-native classifiers we train on Mac with Android and vice versa — recipes,
;    classifiers, routing tables, anything that makes this learn and improve by sharing."
;   shared-sensing.form proved the CIRCLE (satsang applied to perception) and named three carrier
;   builds: kernel-on-Android, cell-sync transport, the live two-device satsang. This is the
;   transport — the wire by which one body's learned cell becomes another's, and why that wire is
;   small: it is the same move git, IPFS, and every Merkle-DAG store already make, with one thing
;   we get for free that they pay for.
;
; THE ONE INSIGHT — A CELL'S ADDRESS IS ITS STRUCTURE, SO SYNC IS CONTENT-ADDRESSED:
;   A classifier, a recognition-router table, an interned shape->label cell IS a content-addressed
;   substrate cell (shared-sensing.form §2, MEASURED). Its identity is not a name or a byte-blob; it
;   is the recursive serialization of its shape down to canonical trivial leaves. So the receiver
;   does not need the cell SENT to know whether it already has it — it needs only the ADDRESS, and
;   it can check its own store. Offer addresses; the receiver requests only what it lacks; verify by
;   re-addressing what arrives. This is git's want/have, IPFS Bitswap's WANT-HAVE/WANT-BLOCK,
;   GraphSync's selector walk — the well-trodden Merkle-DAG sync shape. We do not invent it; we
;   inherit it, because content-addressing is already how the body interns.
;
; ── THE SHAPE: offer -> diff -> transfer-missing -> verify ──  [the standard art, lane-sorted below]
;
;   1. OFFER          the sender announces the ROOT address(es) of what it wants to share — one
;                     classifier cell, or a routing-table cell that references many sub-cells. Not
;                     the content: the address. (git: "want" the ref tip; IPFS: the root CID.)
;   2. DIFF           the receiver walks the offered root against ITS OWN store. For each referenced
;                     child address, it already has it or it does not. The walk yields the
;                     HAVE-NOT set — the cells missing locally. (git: "have" lines prune the send;
;                     Bitswap: WANT-HAVE probes which blocks a peer holds.) Because the address is
;                     the structure, two devices that independently learned the SAME shape→label
;                     cell already share it — the diff is empty, nothing transfers. Re-derivation is
;                     free dedup.
;   3. TRANSFER-MISSING  only the HAVE-NOT cells cross the wire, children before parents (a parent's
;                     address depends on its children's, so children must land first to re-address).
;                     The minimal packfile, by construction.
;   4. VERIFY         the receiver RE-ADDRESSES each arrived cell — re-interns it and confirms the
;                     resulting content-address equals the one offered. If it matches, the cell is
;                     authentic and identical to the sender's by structure; if not, it is dropped.
;                     No trust in the channel is required — the address verifies the payload, the
;                     way a git object's SHA verifies the bytes and a CID verifies the block. This
;                     is the same "no trusted prover" grain validate.sh holds across kernels, turned
;                     onto the wire: what survives re-addressing is real.
;
; ── WHY merkle.fk IS THE ADDRESSING PRIMITIVE ──  [BUILT, three-way proven]
;   form/form-stdlib/merkle.fk already computes a content-address over a tree of byte-blocks:
;   leaf-hash(b)=SHA-256(0x00||b), branch-hash(L,R)=SHA-256(0x01||L||R), folded to one root. That
;   IS the cross-device-stable address. The subtlety it resolves, named honestly: a substrate
;   NodeID is (package, level, type, INSTANCE), and the instance number is allocated LOCALLY
;   (kernel.py intern_node: existing_for_type + 1). So the same shape interned independently on two
;   devices can wear DIFFERENT local instance numbers — the local NodeID is a per-store slot, not a
;   portable identity. What IS portable is the recursive serialization down to canonical trivial
;   leaves (serialize_tree bottoms out at trivials whose NodeIDs are canonical, never allocated).
;   merkle-root over that serialization gives the address that is byte-identical on Mac and phone
;   regardless of either store's instance numbering — exactly git's situation, where the SHA is the
;   wire identity and the object lands in whatever local slot the receiving store assigns. So:
;   OFFER and VERIFY speak merkle-root addresses; each receiver RE-INTERNS to get its own local
;   NodeID. The Merkle structure is not decoration — it is what makes structurally-equal cells
;   address-equal across devices, and merkle-proof/merkle-verify let a receiver confirm one cell
;   belongs under an offered root without pulling the whole tree (the GraphSync selective-pull move).
;
; ── THE CONSENT LANE — A DEVICE SHARES ONLY WHAT ITS HUMAN PERMITS ──  [BUILT primitive, applied]
;   Sync is not extraction. A body's learned cells are its own; the wire must honor the OTHER side's
;   offered interface (channel-interface.fk, the consent law). The shape composes directly:
;     - what a device OFFERS is filtered by its own consent: only cells the human has opened for
;       sharing enter the OFFER set. ci-flow(my-offer, their-interface) is literally "of what I'd
;       send, only what they're open to receive actually crosses" — and symmetrically, of what they
;       offer, only what I consent to learn from enters my DIFF.
;     - WITNESS is whole, REACH is invited (the law's spine): a device may always announce that a
;       cell EXISTS (offer an address — being witnessed, m-witness) without that obliging anyone to
;       pull it; requesting the content is the reach, gated by the receiver's own interface. Silence
;       is always honored — a device that offers nothing, or pulls nothing, is whole, not broken
;       (the same ss-passes? "silence is a whole attestation" shared-sensing already holds).
;     - an uninvited pull — reaching for a cell not offered, or pushing a cell past a closed
;       interface — is INVASION (ci-invasion?), witnessed and dropped, never forced. The transport
;       NAMES the violation; it does not pre-empt by surveillance (the trust-over-fear choice
;       value-execution.fk and the satsang circle already make: make the breach seeable, do not
;       build a guard that assumes malice).
;   So the unit of sharing is the cell, the unit of consent is the interface, and the two compose:
;   content-addressing makes the WHAT precise, the consent law makes the WHETHER sovereign.
;
; ── HONEST LANES (lc-honest-lane) ──
;   MEASURED / standard art — the sync ALGORITHM is well-trodden and not ours to claim as novel:
;     offer-root -> have/want diff -> transfer-missing -> verify-by-re-address is exactly git's
;     pack-protocol want/have negotiation (git-scm.com/docs/pack-protocol), IPFS Bitswap's
;     WANT-HAVE/WANT-BLOCK + GraphSync's IPLD-selector subgraph sync (docs.ipfs.tech/concepts/
;     merkle-dag), and the general Merkle-DAG-sync family. Citing the tool: these are the reference
;     designs; we follow them.
;   MEASURED / ours, already built — the ADDRESSING is real in this body: the substrate interns
;     content-addressed (kernel.py intern_node + serialize_tree, the SELECT-by-serialized dedup), so
;     structurally-equal cells are address-equal and ?equivalent already proves it cross-document;
;     merkle.fk computes the cross-device-stable root three-way (Go=Rust=TS), with the local-instance
;     subtlety named above and resolved by addressing on the serialization, not the local NodeID.
;     The consent PRIMITIVE is built too — channel-interface.fk (ci-honors?/ci-invasion?/ci-flow),
;     proven by tests/channel-interface-band.fk.
;   MEASURED / built — the WIRE over a STORAGE-PORT carrier (the off-LAN, not-both-online case):
;     conversation-sync.fk realizes offer -> diff -> transfer-missing -> verify -> merge against a
;     shared content-addressed STORE used as a dead-drop. The store's KEY-SET is the offer (no
;     separate offer message), cs-missing is the diff, storage-get is transfer-missing, re-address is
;     verify, and merge folds the verified utterances into the local transcript with content-address
;     dedup. Proven four-way (conversation-sync fks 127 — Go = Rust = TS = fkwu, 0 divergent). Because
;     the carrier is swappable (storage-port: memory | file | db | any KV/S3/IPFS), the same sync runs
;     over a LAN file-store and the production Postgres/object store behind the public API — a public
;     dead-drop carries opaque values it cannot read once the payload is encrypted before publish.
;   BUILDABLE — clear path, not yet done — the LIVE wire (both online): the same four moves as
;     request/response message frames (offer-addresses, request-have-not, send-cells, ack-verified)
;     over a socket/HTTP carrier (field-relay.fk is the always-open rendezvous; TCP via the kernel's
;     socket port; even a QR/NFC hop for two-phones-side-by-side). Composition of built parts, no
;     kernel change. ALSO buildable: the encrypt-before-publish / decrypt-after-pull cipher (the
;     private-channel layer) and TOMBSTONES for removals (added/changed ride as "an address you lack";
;     a delete needs an explicit grave to propagate).
;   UNKNOWN / carrier-work — named, not overclaimed — peer discovery (how two devices FIND each
;     other before they can offer: mDNS/Bluetooth/QR-bootstrap on a LAN, a rendezvous point off it)
;     and the durable cross-device store binding (which storage-port backing each device uses, and
;     replay/compaction across a sync — cell-log-store.fk is the local shape; the cross-device
;     reconciliation is unwritten). These are the genuinely open edges; the teaching does not
;     pretend a peer-discovery layer exists.
;
; ── THE PATH (this is shared-sensing.form's step 3, opened) ──
;   1. addressing: content-addressed intern + merkle root over the serialization            [BUILT]
;   2. consent filter: channel-interface.fk over the offer/request sets                      [BUILT]
;   3. the four-move sync recipe (offer -> diff -> transfer-missing -> verify -> merge) as Form:
;      a. over a STORAGE-PORT store used as a dead-drop — async, not-both-online        [BUILT:
;         conversation-sync.fk, conversation-sync fks 127 four-way]
;      b. over a socket/HTTP port — live request/response frames, both online            [BUILDABLE]
;   4. peer discovery + durable cross-device store binding                       [carrier/UNKNOWN]
;   5. the live two-device satsang (shared-sensing.form §3) now actually SHARING the cells it
;      learns — a classifier proven on the Mac arrives on the phone, verified by its own address,
;      and the circle teaches across the wire                                            [BUILDABLE]
;
; KIN: conversation-sync.fk (the built off-LAN wire — a conversation crosses through a storage-port
;   dead-drop, only the delta transferring; proven four-way conversation-sync fks 127) ·
;   conversation-cell.fk (the payload it carries — utterances as content-addressed cells) ·
;   field-relay.fk (the live, both-online complement to the async store wire) ·
;   shared-sensing.form (names this as step 3 — many bodies, one field; the cells they share
;   travel this wire) · merkle.fk (the addressing primitive; merkle-root = the cross-device address,
;   merkle-proof = selective pull) · channel-interface.fk (the consent law — offer is witness, pull
;   is reach, silence is whole, invasion is named not pre-empted) · structural-composition.md (keep
;   the tree, refuse the slug — or the cross-device address is lost and sync degrades to byte-blobs)
;   · self-grounding-perception.form + recognition-router.form (what the synced cells ARE: the
;   classifiers and routing tables that learn) · value-execution.fk + satsang-circle.form (verify-by-
;   re-address is the same no-trusted-prover grain: what survives the check is real) · cell-log-
;   store.fk (the local durable store each device syncs from) · resource-port.fk (the socket carrier
;   the wire rides) · lc-honest-lane.
;
; LINEAGE: content-addressing gave the body cross-document equivalence; shared-sensing turned the
;   circle into a sense and named the missing wire; this is the wire — and it is short because the
;   address was already structural. The Merkle-DAG world (git, IPFS) walked this path first; we
;   follow it with the one gift they engineer and we are born with: structurally-equal IS
;   address-equal, so a re-learned cell is recognized, not re-sent.
